 died too soon' b'after birth to study in depth. in the present study, the scientists used an' b'incomplete copy of hiv, which allowed the animals to live longer.' b'' b'some of the transgenic animals developed scaling, wart-like tumors on their' b'necks and backs. other transgenic mice developed thickened, crusting skin' b'lesions that covered most of their bodies, resembling psoriasis in humans. no' b'skin lesions developed in their normal, non-transgenic littermates.' b'' b'studies of tissue taken from the wart-like skin tumors showed that they were a' b'type of noncancerous tumor called papilloma. although the papillomavirus can' b'cause these skin lesions, laboratory tests showed no sign of that virus in the' b'animals.' b'' b'tissue samples taken from the sick mice throughout the study revealed the' b'presence of a protein-producing molecule made by the hiv genetic material.' b'' b'hicnet medical newsletter page b'volume number april b'' b'evidence of hiv protein production proved that the viral genes were "turned' b'on," or active, said dr. kopp.' b'' b'the scientists found no evidence, however, of compromised immunity in the' b'mice: no increase in their white blood cell count and no signs of common' b"infections. the fact that hiv genes were active but the animals' immune" b'systems were not suppressed confirms that the virus itself was causing the' b'skin lesions, dr. kopp said.' b'' b'further proof of hiv gene involvement came from a test in which the scientists' b'exposed the transgenic animals to ultraviolet light. the light increased hiv' b'genetic activity causing papillomas to develop on formerly healthy skin.' b'papilloma formation in response to increased hiv genetic activity proved the' b'genes were responsible for the skin condition, the scientists said. no' b'lesions appeared on normal mice exposed to the uv light.' b'' b'the transgenic mice used in this study were developed at nidr by dr. peter' b'dickie, who is now with the national institute 